@Isabeau

Which ties into why NELL is a nickname for Eleanor, as we found out recently. 

In ye olde days, people said, “mine Eleanor,” “mine Edward,” etc., which were mistaken for “my Neleanor” and “my Nedward” and then shortened.

@Francis

P. S.  It just occurred to me--in that time even K-6 generally walked to school.

🙁

@Francis

I think we got those when I was a patrol boy, too. It was a Sam Browne belt. <a href="https://cdn.datadirectory.co.uk/images/500/prs-rsbb.png" target="_blank">https://cdn.datadirectory.co.uk/images/500/prs-rsbb.png</a>

Now that I think about it, for some reason I don't think any of my younger brothers were attracted to that activity.

@Rahul

